Comment: Lit. 'one person' 02.100, meaning the count of the fingers and toes.
Also means 'to speak'; cf. 18.210. atəʔtihāne, 'to arrive for trading'.
Also hənɨn-nə; and tɨwəʔhiyɨ, with the sense of bathe, swim.
The root is -ənu-; also ənuʔk, 'rise', with the sense of action generated by the thing rising.

Refers to washing things/objects, distinct from human beings. Different terms for w. parts of the human body: w-onwatɨ̄-nə, w. hands; w-entatɨ̄-nə, w. one's own mouth; inčatɨ-dɨ, w. someone else's mouth.
Is used with both a subj. and object; eši is used with subj. only.
Also ešičako, used for the sense of 'break or be weak'.
Also w-awō-nə, with the sense of the s. happening to someone or something.
Refers to a spider that doesn't bite.
Refers to fish in the water; lit. 'people who live in the river'. Fish caught and out of the river is oʔtāho.
Prob. from Span. 'loro'. Other kinds of parrots are kayʔčay; kudēwa.
A blue-grey heron. Also mādi, small white h.; and ahīša, large white h.
Dual form: speaker plus one listener. Plural is kɨnwanno, includes more than one listener.
Also kəmusaʔkə; and kənʔkwə, used by the more traditional speakers.
Reference term. Term of address is mama.

Also -yaʔkwa-dɨ; both terms mean 'burn' in any context, with sense of being consumed by fire. Also yaʔka-dɨ, means 'burn' in the context of cleaning garden; may also be translated as 'to fell, cut down'.
Refers to wood ashes; šēʔseʔdɨ is used for ashes of cassava.
Also dōta, for 'soul'; əkatomhə is usually used to refer to spirit.
Noun form; verbal form is koneʔda.
